{"bookId": "67656cf0a790fd9b172cf0d2","moduleId": "67656cf0a790fd9b172cf0d2","subjectId": "67656cf8a790fd9b172cf0d3","chapterId": "67656cf8a790fd9b172cf0d5","subject": "Physics","chapter": "Modern Physics","count": 9,"questions": [{"id": 0,"subject": "Physics","chapter": "Modern Physics","exam": "Engineering","examName": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","q": "The first three spectral lines of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>-atom in the Balmer series are given <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> considering the Bohr atomic model, the wave lengths of first and third spectral lines <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mfrac><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfrac></mfenced></math> are related by a factor of approximately <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>. The value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>,&nbsp;to the nearest integer, is ________.","options": ["A","B","C","D"],"answer": 0,"solution": "<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><msup><mi>z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><msup><mi>z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>36</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>3</mn><mi>rd</mi></msup></math> line</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><msup><mi>z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>5</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><msup><mi>z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfrac><mn>21</mn><mn>100</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>21</mn><mn>100</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>36</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>512</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>15</mn></math></p>","difficulty": "Medium","source": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","_marksId": "648b5a69417cc3fb48d66e80","paperSource": "JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 1)"},{"id": 0,"subject": "Physics","chapter": "Modern Physics","exam": "Engineering","examName": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","q": "<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></math> is the ratio of energies of photons produced due to transition of an electron of hydrogen atom from its</p><p>(i) third permitted energy level to the second level and</p><p>(ii) the highest permitted energy level to the second permitted level.</p><p>The value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp;will be</p>","options": ["A","B","C","D"],"answer": 0,"solution": "<blockquote><p>Energy of a photon released in transition of electron in hydrogen atom is given by,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mo>&#8734;</mo></mfrac></mstyle></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac></mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mi>x</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p></blockquote>","difficulty": "Easy","source": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","_marksId": "648b5a6c417cc3fb48d67858","paperSource": "JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 2)"},{"id": 0,"subject": "Physics","chapter": "Modern Physics","exam": "Engineering","examName": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","q": "A light of energy <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>75</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math> is incident on a hydrogen atom in its ground state. The atom absorbs the radiation and reaches to one of its excited states. The angular momentum of the atom in the excited state is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mi>&#960;</mi></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>17</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eVs</mi></math>.&nbsp;The value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> is ______ (use&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eVs</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>)","options": ["A","B","C","D"],"answer": 0,"solution": "<p>Let the electron jumped to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>n</mi><mrow><mi>t</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;excited state.</p><p>In the ground state, energy&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math></p><p>So, using relation&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>75</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9375</mn><mo>=</mo><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#8658;</mo><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>16</mn></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p>Now,&nbsp;angular momentum,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>h</mi></mrow><mi>&#960;</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>828</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>17</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mi>&#960;</mi></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eVs</mi></math></p><p>Hence, the value of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>828</mn></math>.</p>","difficulty": "Hard","source": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","_marksId": "648b5a6e417cc3fb48d67f07","paperSource": "JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 1)"},{"id": 0,"subject": "Physics","chapter": "Modern Physics","exam": "Engineering","examName": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","q": "In Bohr&#39;s atomic model, the electron is assumed to revolve in a circular orbit of radius <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#8728;</mo></mover><mo>.</mo></math>&nbsp;If the speed of electron is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>.</mo></math>&nbsp;Then the current associated with the electron will be__________&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mA</mi><mo>.</mo></math> [Take <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#960;</mi></math> as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"\"><mfrac><mn>22</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math>","options": ["A","B","C","D"],"answer": 0,"solution": "<p>Time taken to revolve in circular orbit is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#969;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>22</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>11</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>16</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p><p>Now, current associated with the electron is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>e</mi><mi>T</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>16</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mA</mi></math><br />Hence, the current is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>112</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mA</mi></math>.</p>","difficulty": "Medium","source": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","_marksId": "648b5a6b417cc3fb48d675e1","paperSource": "JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)"},{"id": 0,"subject": "Physics","chapter": "Modern Physics","exam": "Engineering","examName": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","q": "The first member of the Balmer series of hydrogen atom has a wavelength of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6561</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#8728;</mo></mover></math>. The wavelength of the second member of the Balmer series (in nm) is_____________","options": ["A","B","C","D"],"answer": 0,"solution": "<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><msup><mrow><mi>Z</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msubsup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msubsup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>16</mn></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>20</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>27</mn></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>20</mn><mn>27</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6561</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#8728;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mn>4860</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#8728;</mo></mover></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>486</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math>","difficulty": "Medium","source": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","_marksId": "648b5a69417cc3fb48d66d43","paperSource": "JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 2)"},{"id": 0,"subject": "Physics","chapter": "Modern Physics","exam": "Engineering","examName": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","q": "A certain metallic surface is illuminated by monochromatic radiation of wavelength $\\lambda$. The stopping potential for photoelectric current for this radiation is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><msub><mrow><mo mathvariant=\"italic\">&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">V</mi></mrow><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>.</mo></math>&nbsp;If the same surface is illuminated with a radiation of wavelength <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>&#955;</mi><mo>,</mo></math>&nbsp;the stopping potential is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>.</mo></math>&nbsp;The threshold wavelength of this surface for photoelectric effect is___________<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#955;</mi><mo>.</mo></math>","options": ["A","B","C","D"],"answer": 0,"solution": "<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KE</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mi>&#981;</mi><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>e</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8230;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>e</mi><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8230;</mo><mfenced><mi>ii</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>Using <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced><mtext>&#160;and</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi>ii</mi></mfenced></math>,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mi>t</mi></msub></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mi>t</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></p>","difficulty": "Medium","source": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","_marksId": "648b5a6a417cc3fb48d670fa","paperSource": "JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)"},{"id": 0,"subject": "Physics","chapter": "Modern Physics","exam": "Engineering","examName": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","q": "<p>From the given data, the amount of energy required to break the nucleus of aluminium <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi>Al</mi><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>13</mn><mn>27</mn></mmultiscripts></math> is __________<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>&nbsp;</p><p>Mass of neutron <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>00866</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></math><br />Mass of proton <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>00726</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></math><br />Mass of Aluminium nucleus <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>27</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>18846</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></math><br />(Assume <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></math> corresponds to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>J</mi></math> of energy)<br />(Round off to the nearest integer)</p>","options": ["A","B","C","D"],"answer": 0,"solution": "<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>Z</mi><msub><mi>m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">P</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Z</mi><mo>)</mo><msub><mi>m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">n</mi></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>M</mi><mi>Al</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>00726</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>00866</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>27</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>18846</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>27</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>21562</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>27</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>18846</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02716</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>27</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>16</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p>","difficulty": "Medium","source": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","_marksId": "648b5a6b417cc3fb48d6736e","paperSource": "JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)"},{"id": 0,"subject": "Physics","chapter": "Modern Physics","exam": "Engineering","examName": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","q": "<p>Two lighter nuclei combine to form a comparatively heavier nucleus by the relation given below:</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi>X</mi><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mmultiscripts><mo>+</mo><mmultiscripts><mi>X</mi><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mmultiscripts><mo>=</mo><mmultiscripts><mi>Y</mi><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>2</mn><mn>4</mn></mmultiscripts></math></p><p>&nbsp;The binding energies per nucleon <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi>X</mi><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mmultiscripts></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi>Y</mi><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>2</mn><mn>4</mn></mmultiscripts></math> are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mi>MeV</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>MeV</mi></math> respectively. The energy released in this process is_____ <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MeV</mi></math>.</p>","options": ["A","B","C","D"],"answer": 0,"solution": "<blockquote><p>Energy released in the given process <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math> Binding energy of product <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo></math> Binding energy of reactants.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>26</mn><mi>MeV</mi></math></p></blockquote>","difficulty": "Easy","source": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","_marksId": "648b5a6d417cc3fb48d679c0","paperSource": "JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 2)"},{"id": 0,"subject": "Physics","chapter": "Modern Physics","exam": "Engineering","examName": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","q": "<p>A common example of alpha decay is</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><msup><mrow/><mn>238</mn></msup><mn>92</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">U</mi><msub><msup><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>234</mn></msup><mn>90</mn></msub><mi>Th</mi><msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></msub><msup><mi>He</mi><mn>4</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>Q</mi></math></p><p>Given:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><msup><mrow></mrow><mn>238</mn></msup><mn>92</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">U</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>238</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05060</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><msup><mrow></mrow><mn>234</mn></msup><mn>90</mn></msub><mi>Th</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>234</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04360</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><msup><mrow></mrow><mn>4</mn></msup><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>He</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>00260</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>931</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mfrac><mi>MeV</mi><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math></p><p>The energy released <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>Q</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;during the alpha decay of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><msup><mrow></mrow><mn>238</mn></msup><mn>92</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">U</mi></math>&nbsp;is _____ <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MeV</mi></math>.</p>","options": ["A","B","C","D"],"answer": 0,"solution": "<p>The formula to calculate the Q-value of the given&nbsp;nuclear reaction can be written as</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Q</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">U</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>m</mi><mi>Th</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>m</mi><mi>He</mi></msub></mrow></mfenced><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Substitute the values of the known parameters into equation (1) to&nbsp;calculate the required Q-value for the reaction.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><mi>Q</mi></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfenced><mrow><mn>238</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05060</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>234</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04360</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>00260</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></mrow></mfenced><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0044</mn><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>931</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeV</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>&#8776;</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeV</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p>","difficulty": "Medium","source": "Top 100 Numerical Qs of JEE Main 2023-2020","_marksId": "648b5a71417cc3fb48d6860c","paperSource": "JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)"}]}